flowRoot.flowPara: This plot shows my posting history broken down on a monthly basis for every year I have been active on Instagram. My relationship with the platform has changed over the years since I first set up my account in May of 2016 but I have always used it as a means of documenting my rock climbing and alpinism adventures. From this plot we can see a few notable spikes in posting frequency that can be directly attributed to life experiences, most notabely the Covid-19 pandemic lockdown of March, 2020. Another area of note, but not as easily seen as the spikes, are the lack of data from January until April of 2019. During this time I was taking a break from social media and for the latter half of this time rafting through the Grand Canyon.

To the right we have a monthly sentiment analysis break down of the text in my posts. I was hoping to reveal a pattern between my posts' porportional sentiment, the frequency of posting, and the number of followers gained (the plot below) but there seem to be no striking patterns that leap out from this analysis. I think there are multiple factors as to why this is, mainly that I do not post frequently enough to have a robust sample but also due to mislabeling artifacts in the sentiment analysis.

Here we explore the followers I have gained again broken down on a monthly basis for each year on the platform. While I do not use Instagram to "cultivate a following" or for monetization, I do have a public account that anyone can follow. On studying this figure and comparing it to the first figure above we can see that there seems to be a positive correlation between the frequency of my posting and the number of new followers I gain in that month. Moreover, this effect looks to be more pronounced in the years 2018 and 2017, which is when I would use hashtags in my posts. Lastly, this correlation breaks down for March of 2020 during lockdown. While I may have been posting on the app more I was primarily just posting stories for my current friends to see.

Above is a further textual analysis of how I interact with Instagram shown through more sentiment analysis and the most common vocabulary used in the form of wordclouds. Each category shows a similar ditribution of sentiment but it is interesting that the proportion of positive sentiment is higher in the Comments category. I believe this reflects the general positive attitude I look for in friends. More interestingly, the wordcloud analysis displays some interesting, niche vocabulary. Like I previously mentioned, I primarily use Instagram to document my climbing and alpinism and this is directly reflected in the wordclouds. The most evident example is that the word "climb" is present in all the categories. Instagram definitely knows this, as I have noticed that most of my advertisments are either climbing or outdoor related.
